<div class="container">
    <h1>Interfaces in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>An <strong>interface</strong> is a contract that defines a set of methods and properties that a class must implement. Interfaces allow you to achieve abstraction and multiple inheritance in C#.</p>

    <h2>Example: Creating and Implementing an Interface</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Define an Interface</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public interface IVehicle
{
    void StartEngine();
    void StopEngine();
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Implement the Interface</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Car : IVehicle
{
    public void StartEngine()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Car engine started.");
    }

    public void StopEngine()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Car engine stopped.");
    }
}

// Usage
IVehicle myCar = new Car();
myCar.StartEngine();
myCar.StopEngine();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points About Interfaces</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>An interface only contains method and property signatures, not implementation.</li>
        <li>A class implementing an interface must provide implementation for all members.</li>
        <li>Interfaces allow for flexible and maintainable code through abstraction.</li>
        <li>Multiple interfaces can be implemented by a single class.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <p>Create an interface <code>IPayment</code> with methods <code>Pay()</code> and <code>Refund()</code>. Then create a class <code>CreditCardPayment</code> that implements this interface and provides messages for each method.</p>

